5000|$|In 1990 {{he broke}} the news in that Saddam Hussein was {{determined}} to re-open Iraq’s boundary dispute with Kuwait, the issue that led to <b>the</b> <b>Gulf</b> <b>Crisis</b> and War of 1990-1991. As editor of Middle East Monitor in the 1990s, he reported <b>on</b> <b>the</b> emergence of Kurdish autonomy in northern Iraq, the changing fortunes of the Arab World, Iran in an era characterised by international sanctions, and the slow recovery of trust between OPEC producer states and industrialised consuming nations.|$|R
50|$|Mr. Kimmitt {{resumed his}} public service career in 1989, serving as Under Secretary of State for Political Affairs until 1991. For his service during <b>the</b> <b>Gulf</b> <b>Crisis</b> and War, President George H. W. Bush {{presented}} Mr. Kimmitt with the Presidential Citizens Medal, the Nation’s second highest civilian award. He served from 1991 to 1993 as United States Ambassador to Germany and {{was awarded the}} U.S. Defense Department Distinguished Public Service Award as well as Germany’s Order of Merit.|$|R
